WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.710 --> 00:00:04.430
The third area of staffing that people
spend a lot of time thinking about

2
00:00:04.430 --> 00:00:06.170
is attrition, and it makes sense.

3
00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:09.870
You spend a lot of time and effort
making sure you hired the right people.

4
00:00:09.870 --> 00:00:12.080
You're then worried about
are they in the right job,

5
00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:13.360
how do we promote them, and so on.

6
00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:16.890
Well, having got them there,
you kind of want them to stay in the job

7
00:00:16.890 --> 00:00:21.490
Certainly organizations have discovered
that turnover is very costly.

8
00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:24.120
Why, because of all
the things that it leads to.

9
00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:25.850
So what does turnover lead to.

10
00:00:25.850 --> 00:00:27.530
It lead to increase hiring costs.

11
00:00:27.530 --> 00:00:29.640
Okay, you've gotta replace the people.

12
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:33.400
You've then gotta train the new people
in the kind of skills that the people

13
00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:34.060
who left had.

14
00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:37.860
And then there's gonna be a bunch of
things that you can't even train.

15
00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:42.460
Some of the unique knowledge that somebody
had built up over years, at least months

16
00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:47.150
of working there, which then has to be
relearned or maybe is never reacquired.

17
00:00:47.150 --> 00:00:50.510
And then, on top of that, there are the
relationships that they had built up,

18
00:00:50.510 --> 00:00:54.500
both with their colleagues that made
the work easier, and also with customers.

19
00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:58.220
And so we know turnover impacts
productivity, it impacts quality, and

20
00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:00.470
it impacts customer relationships.

21
00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:04.610
And there have been a wide variety of
studies that demonstrate a strong negative

22
00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:08.300
effects of performance on work group
performance and profitability.

23
00:01:08.300 --> 00:01:11.840
So this is something you really
want to worry about as a manager.

24
00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:16.740
Of course, in order for
finding out more about it to be valuable,

25
00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:20.080
they need to be things you can
actually do with that knowledge.

26
00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:22.280
And there are when you know more about it,

27
00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:26.070
you can pull the levers to reduce
turnover more effectively.

28
00:01:26.070 --> 00:01:28.880
So, in particular,
when we know who leaves and

29
00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:31.360
why, that can inform our hiring decisions.

30
00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.940
One of the easiest ways to
address a turnover problem

31
00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:35.660
is by looking at your hiring.

32
00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:39.260
Are we bringing in people who
are likely to be leaving?

33
00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:42.190
The same time we can think about what
kinds of interventions we want to make

34
00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:43.900
inside the organization.

35
00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.860
Certain groups are much
more likely to leave,

36
00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:49.060
are there needs of those
that are being unmet?

37
00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:52.820
Is there something about the conditions
of those jobs, either pay or

38
00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:58.530
the work itself, that we can really
change in order to address turnover.

39
00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:02.150
Sometimes we find there are particular
managers who seem to have a problem.

40
00:02:02.150 --> 00:02:04.440
Either we can move them out or
we can train them, and

41
00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.370
help them think about how to mitigate and
reduce that turnover.

42
00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:08.900
Okay?

43
00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:13.430
And more broadly the extent to which we're
gonna spend time and money on retention,

44
00:02:13.430 --> 00:02:19.020
figuring out who our biggest flight risks
are will help us in targeting that money,

45
00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:20.090
and that effort effectively.

46
00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:26.430
So I wanna spend a couple of minutes just
thinking about why do people leave, and

47
00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:29.640
how's that going to help us
understand the drives of it?

48
00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.120
The simplest view of a attrition is
obviously that people leave their jobs

49
00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:38.095
when they find something else
that they would rather be doing.

50
00:02:38.095 --> 00:02:42.150
That' s the kind of depth of insight they
pay off the academics the big bucks for.

51
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:45.250
If you think about that,

52
00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:49.630
then there are two things that are really
going to drive whether or not people stay.

53
00:02:49.630 --> 00:02:50.440
Okay?

54
00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:52.750
One is the attractiveness of
the outside opportunities.

55
00:02:52.750 --> 00:02:56.160
And so
you will see attrition is highly cyclical.

56
00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:57.660
When the economy is doing well and

57
00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:00.780
there are more job opportunities outside,
people will leave more.

58
00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:02.800
It's also gonna affect who leaves.

59
00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.070
Those jobs which are in high demand,
where it's easier for

60
00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:08.750
people to move to industries
that are growing rapidly and

61
00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:11.870
have a lot of jobs,
those are gonna see high attrition.

62
00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:14.370
And there may also be
reasons that people leave,

63
00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:18.130
because they just plan that they
want to move on to the next thing.

64
00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:20.890
So the attractiveness of
those things drives it.

65
00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:24.800
On the other hand the fact that something
is more attractive in your current job

66
00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:26.920
may say something about your current job.

67
00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.900
So the less happy you
are with the existing job

68
00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:31.210
the more likely you are to move.

69
00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:36.240
So things about your satisfaction today,
or your satisfaction with

70
00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:41.180
kind of your future trajectory It's going
to tell you something about who leaves.

71
00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:44.560
As you think about what it
is that makes people leave.

72
00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:47.940
What would be some of the things in
terms of the current job that you would

73
00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:49.020
think would be the most important?

74
00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.100
Any thoughts, anybody?

